    {
      num: 5,
      label: "Q5: Atomic Structure & Radioactivity",
      q: "(a) Rutherford's gold foil experiment (c. 1909): Most alpha particles passed straight through, a small number deflected at large angles, a very tiny number rebounded back.\n(i) Based on Thomson's model, which observation was most unexpected?\n(ii) What did Rutherford conclude about atomic structure?\n\n(b) Define (i) isotopes, (ii) relative atomic mass.\n\n(c) Write the s, p electron configuration for calcium in its ground state. How many (i) main energy levels, (ii) orbitals are occupied? Predict how calcium behaves in a chemical reaction.\n\n(d)(i) Define radioactivity.\n(ii) Complete the nuclear equation for alpha decay of Rn-222.\n(iii) Why can't lead (Pb) be changed to gold (Au) by chemical reactions?",
      a: "(a)(i) The very tiny number that rebounded back along their original paths was most unexpected. Thomson's plum pudding model (uniform positive charge) could not explain particles bouncing back.\n(a)(ii) The atom is mostly empty space with a tiny, dense, positively charged nucleus at the centre, containing most of the mass.\n\n(b)(i) Isotopes: atoms of the same element with the same atomic number but different mass numbers (different numbers of neutrons).\n(b)(ii) Relative atomic mass: the average mass of the isotopes of an element, weighted by their natural abundances, relative to 1/12 the mass of a carbon-12 atom.\n\n(c) Configuration: 1s2 2s2 2p6 3s2 3p6 4s2.\n(i) 4 main energy levels (shells) occupied.\n(ii) 10 orbitals occupied (1 + 1 + 3 + 1 + 3 + 1 = 10).\nCalcium will lose its 2 outer electrons (4s2) to achieve a stable noble gas configuration (argon), forming Ca2+ ions. It acts as a reducing agent.\n\n(d)(i) Radioactivity: the spontaneous disintegration (breaking up) of unstable nuclei with the emission of radiation.\n(d)(ii) Rn-222 -> Po-218 + He-4. The daughter element is polonium-218 (86 - 2 = 84 protons).\n(d)(iii) Chemical reactions involve only rearrangements of electrons in the outer shells. Changing lead to gold requires changing the number of protons in the nucleus, which is a nuclear change, not a chemical one.\n\nWhy: Rutherford's experiment disproved the plum pudding model. Only a tiny, dense, positively charged nucleus could cause alpha particles to rebound. Chemical reactions cannot change elements because they do not affect the nucleus."
    },
    {
      num: 6,
      label: "Q6: Fuels, Hydrocarbons & Thermochemistry",
      q: "(a) Compare petrol (light gasoline/naphtha) and diesel (gas oil) in terms of:\n(i) average molecular mass, (ii) boiling point.\n\n(b)(i) Explain the term octane number.\nGive the IUPAC name and draw the structure of the alkane with octane number:\n(ii) zero, (iii) 100.\n(iv) What structural feature gives the 100-octane alkane its high octane number?\n\n(c) Hydrogen fuel cells. Equation: H2(g) + 1/2 O2(g) -> H2O(l). Steam reforming: CH4(g) + H2O(g) -> CO(g) + 3H2(g), dH = +206.2 kJ.\n(i) Why doesn't elemental H2 occur naturally on Earth as a fuel?\n(ii) Give a major source of H2 other than steam reforming.\n(iii) Define heat of reaction.\n(iv) Why is the same energy released in a fuel cell as when H2 is burned?\n(v) Calculate the heat of formation of methane using: Hf(steam) = -241.8, Hf(CO) = -110.5 kJ/mol.",
      a: "(a)(i) Diesel has a higher average molecular mass than petrol.\n(a)(ii) Diesel has a higher boiling point than petrol.\n\n(b)(i) Octane number: a measure of how smoothly a fuel burns without knocking (premature auto-ignition), on a scale of 0 to 100.\n(b)(ii) Octane number 0: heptane (CH3(CH2)5CH3) -- a straight-chain alkane.\n(b)(iii) Octane number 100: 2,2,4-trimethylpentane (isooctane) -- a branched alkane.\n(b)(iv) Branching -- the highly branched structure resists auto-ignition and burns more smoothly.\n\n(c)(i) H2 is too reactive; it readily combines with oxygen and other elements, so free H2 does not accumulate in the atmosphere.\n(c)(ii) Electrolysis of water.\n(c)(iii) Heat of reaction: the heat change when the amounts of reactants shown in a balanced equation react completely.\n(c)(iv) Same reactants (H2 + O2) and same products (H2O) in both processes. By Hess's law, the enthalpy change depends only on the initial and final states, not the pathway.\n(c)(v) Rearrange: CH4(g) + H2O(g) -> CO(g) + 3H2(g). dH = Hf(products) - Hf(reactants). 206.2 = [-110.5 + 0] - [Hf(CH4) + (-241.8)]. 206.2 = -110.5 - Hf(CH4) + 241.8. 206.2 = 131.3 - Hf(CH4). Hf(CH4) = 131.3 - 206.2 = -74.9 kJ/mol.\n\nWhy: Hess's law states total enthalpy change is independent of the route. Whether H2 burns in a flame or reacts in a fuel cell, the overall reaction H2 + O2 -> H2O releases the same energy."
    },
    {
      num: 7,
      label: "Q7: Chemical Equilibrium",
      q: "CO(g) + 2H2(g) <=> CH3OH(g), dH = -94.4 kJ/mol.\n5.0 moles CO and 10.0 moles H2 in a 5.0 L container at 250 degrees C with catalyst. 25% conversion of CO to methanol at equilibrium.\n\n(a) Explain chemical equilibrium in terms of (i) rates of reaction, (ii) concentrations.\n(b)(i) Write the expression for Kc.\n(b)(ii) Calculate the value of Kc.\n(c) The same equilibrium is reached with two different catalysts. What is the advantage of a catalyst?\n(d)(i) State Le Chatelier's principle.\n(d)(ii) How is the yield of methanol affected when more CO is added and equilibrium re-establishes?",
      a: "(a)(i) At equilibrium, the rate of the forward reaction equals the rate of the reverse reaction.\n(a)(ii) At equilibrium, the concentrations of all reactants and products remain constant (though not necessarily equal).\n\n(b)(i) Kc = [CH3OH] / ([CO][H2]^2)\n(b)(ii) 25% of 5.0 mol CO reacts = 1.25 mol. H2 used = 2 x 1.25 = 2.5 mol.\nAt equilibrium: CO = 3.75 mol, H2 = 7.5 mol, CH3OH = 1.25 mol.\nConcentrations (divide by 5.0 L): [CO] = 0.75 M, [H2] = 1.5 M, [CH3OH] = 0.25 M.\nKc = 0.25 / (0.75 x 1.5^2) = 0.25 / (0.75 x 2.25) = 0.25 / 1.6875 = 0.148.\n\n(c) A catalyst speeds up both the forward and reverse reactions equally, so equilibrium is reached faster. It does not change the position of equilibrium or the value of Kc. The advantage is reaching equilibrium more quickly.\n\n(d)(i) Le Chatelier's principle: if a system at equilibrium is subjected to a change in conditions (concentration, temperature, or pressure), the equilibrium will shift in the direction that tends to oppose (partially counteract) the change.\n(d)(ii) Adding more CO increases [CO]. The system shifts to the right (towards products) to partially reduce [CO]. The yield of methanol increases.\n\nWhy: Kc only changes with temperature. Changing concentration or adding a catalyst does not change Kc. Le Chatelier's principle predicts the direction of the shift when conditions change."
    }
