      q: "Answer eight of the following:\n(a) Define (i) atomic number, (ii) mass number.\n(b) Write the formula for the simplest compound of gallium (valency 3) with (i) nitrogen, (ii) oxygen.\n(c) Predict the two possible shapes of molecule ABn where n = 2.\n(d) Identify the energy change: X+(g) -> X2+(g) + e-.\n(e) What is diffusion?\n(f) In a mass spectrometer, identify the processes at stages 2 and 4.\n(g) 25.0 cm3 of 0.12 M solution diluted to 30.0 cm3. Find the new concentration.\n(h) What is an enzyme?\n(i) Draw the structure of propane-1,2,3-triol (glycerol) showing all atoms and bonds.\n(j) Give the oxidation number of sulfur in (i) SO4 2-, (ii) Na2S4O6.\n(k) Calculate the minimum number of molecules of 2-methoxybenzoic acid (Mr = 152) in a 250 g jar of manuka honey, certified to contain at least 1 x 10^-3 g per kg.\n(l) A: Balanced equation(s) for limestone as a scrubber for SO2. OR B: Explain why metallic crystals conduct electricity.",
      a: "(a)(i) Atomic number: the number of protons in the nucleus of an atom.\n(a)(ii) Mass number: the total number of protons and neutrons in the nucleus.\n\n(b)(i) GaN. (ii) Ga2O3.\n\n(c) V-shape (bent/angular) and linear.\n\n(d) Second ionisation energy.\n\n(e) Diffusion: the spreading (movement) of a substance from a region of high concentration to a region of low concentration.\n\n(f) Stage 2: ionisation. Stage 4: separation (by magnetic field based on mass/charge ratio).\n\n(g) C1V1 = C2V2. 25.0 x 0.12 = 30.0 x M. M = 0.1 M.\n\n(h) An enzyme is a biological catalyst -- a protein that alters the rate of a biochemical reaction.\n\n(i) Three carbon chain, each C bonded to H atoms and an OH group: HOCH2-CHOH-CH2OH with all atoms and bonds shown explicitly.\n\n(j)(i) Sulfur in SO4 2-: +6 (VI).\n(j)(ii) In Na2S4O6: average oxidation number = +2.5 (two S at +2, two S at +3).\n\n(k) Mass per kg = 1 x 10^-3 g. Moles per kg = 0.001/152 = 6.6 x 10^-6. Molecules per kg = 6.6 x 10^-6 x 6.0 x 10^23 = 3.96 x 10^18. Per 250 g jar (1/4 kg) = 3.96 x 10^18 / 4 = approx 1 x 10^18 molecules (to 1 significant figure).\n\n(l) A: CaCO3 + SO2 -> CaSO3 + CO2 (balanced, with correct formulae).\nB: Valence electrons in metals are delocalised -- free to move through the lattice of positive metal ions, carrying an electric current.\n\nWhy: For dilution, use C1V1 = C2V2. For oxidation numbers, the sum of all oxidation numbers must equal the overall charge of the ion or molecule."
