      q: "Questions covering water treatment, industrial processes, and environmental chemistry topics.",
      a: "Key points for 2024:\n- Water treatment: screening, sedimentation, flocculation (aluminium sulfate causes small particles to aggregate), filtration (sand/gravel beds), chlorination (kills microorganisms), fluoridation (sodium fluoride or H2SiF6 for dental health), pH adjustment.\n- Sewage treatment: primary (physical removal of solids by screening and settling), secondary (biological treatment using activated sludge -- aerobic bacteria break down organic matter), tertiary (chemical removal of phosphates using aluminium sulfate to precipitate AlPO4).\n- Contact process for sulfuric acid: burn sulfur to get SO2, catalytic oxidation to SO3 (V2O5 catalyst, 450 degrees C, 1-2 atm), dissolve SO3 in concentrated H2SO4 to form oleum, dilute with water.\n- Haber process for ammonia: N2 + 3H2 <=> 2NH3, iron catalyst, 450 degrees C, 200 atm. Compromise: moderate temperature gives reasonable rate and yield.\n- Greenhouse effect, acid rain, ozone depletion -- know the chemistry, causes, and effects.\n- BOD (biochemical oxygen demand): mass of dissolved O2 consumed per litre by microorganisms over 5 days at 20 degrees C. Higher BOD = more organic pollution.\n\nWhy: Industrial processes balance thermodynamics (favourable yield) with kinetics (reasonable rate). The Haber process is the classic example: low temperature favours yield but is too slow, so a compromise temperature with a catalyst is used."
